  <h1>Web application development for JSR286 portlets</h1>
<p>
Rails-portlet runs a webapp, such as Ruby on Rails, in a standard <a href="http://jcp.org/en/jsr/detail?id=286">JSR286 Java portlet</a>. The tools and default configuration have been developed in  <a href="http://www.liferay.com">Liferay</a> &amp; Rails + PostgreSQL. This makes agile portlet development on J2EE platform easier to manage.
</p>
<p>
Liferay handles the user management, page layouts ("window management") and other common portal application principles. This workload is off the development team.
</p>

<h1>What environment does this run in?</h1>
<p>
Liferay 5.x, tested on Tomcat. Rails 2 has been used on a number of projects, deployed on both JRuby servlet and MRI Mongrel dispatchers.<br />
Regarding application development for the Liferay platform and database integration, the v5 schema modeling is working only on PostgreSQL.
</p>

<h1>So how do I get started?</h1>
<p>
The aim of this project is to get development quickly on track, with as much automation as possible.
If you want to build a Rails app and run it on Liferay in portlets,
</p>

