<%= image_tag 'caterpillar/caterpillar.gif', :alt => "", :style => "float: left; overflow: auto;" -%>
<p class="code" style="overflow: auto;">
 gem install caterpillar
</p>
</div>

<p>
and download the latest supported Liferay/Tomcat bundle (v5.2) and Rails v2.3. For usable Rails/Liferay database integration, please use PostgreSQL and install the <em>lportal</em> gem. It provides a set of migrations that are required to run before starting the application. The master branch contains incomplete MySQL support.
<br />
See the <%= link_to 'default setup guide', doc_url(:action => 'defaultsetup') %>.
</p>

<h1>What about other portals?</h1>
<p>
Portals without support for portlet filters introduced in the JSR286 spec cannot be supported.
</p>

<h1>What about other frameworks?</h1>
<p>
If you want to develop, say, a <em>Django</em> app, or a <em>.NET</em> app, nothing is stopping you. Oh well, at least you need to generate the portlet XML manually, but <em>html2jsr286</em> allows you to run arbitrary webapp in a portlet. Caterpillar has the XML rules so you may want to check out the <em><a href="http://github.com/lamikae/rails-portlet/tree/master/example/">example Rails application</a></em>.
</p>

